    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Act Now to Prevent Diabetes</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dick Smith letter notes diet high in refined carbohydrates contributes to rise in diabetes (Aug 24 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Diabetes Rises; Doctors Foresee a Harsh Impact'' (front page, Aug. 24): One major cause of this epidemic has been the promotion for many years of low-fat diets. Reducing fats is not enough. So-called low-fat products are loaded with sugars of various sorts. So are the soft drinks and so many other delights that reportedly supply the average American with 20.5 teaspoons of added sugar a day (or 68.5 pounds per person each year).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Diabetes Rises; Doctors Foresee a Harsh Impact'' (front page, Aug. 24): One major cause of this epidemic has been the promotion for many years of low-fat diets. Reducing fats is not enough. So-called low-fat products are loaded with sugars of various sorts. So are the soft drinks and so many other delights that reportedly supply the average American with 20.5 teaspoons of added sugar a day (or 68.5 pounds per person each year).</p>
        <p>Carbohydrates that can't be used for energy are converted into fat. Lack of enough exercise is part of the problem, but eating habits are the critical part.</p>
        <p>DICK SMITH  Branford, Conn., Aug. 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
